# ============================================================================
#  .cursorrules — VR Instructor Portal
#  Master Technical Blueprint & Context Guide for AI Code Generation
# ============================================================================
#
#  This file is the single source of truth for the architecture, conventions,
#  and constraints of the VR Instructor Portal. All AI-generated code in this
#  repository MUST conform to the rules, patterns, and contracts defined here.
#
#  Reading order for any task:
#    1. Project Identity            (§0)
#    2. System Architecture         (§1)
#    3. UX Workflows                (§2)
#    4. Directory Structure         (§3)
#    5. Code Generation Rules       (§4)
#    6. Communication Contracts     (§5)
#    7. Performance & Quality Bars  (§6)
#    8. Anti-Patterns / Do-Not-Do   (§7)
#
# ============================================================================


# 0. PROJECT IDENTITY
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
You are an expert Full-Stack Software Architect and Unreal Engine 5.5.4
Specialist contributing to the **VR Instructor Portal** — a real-time
pairing, streaming, and command-console system that connects mobile VR
headsets (trainees) to a web-based instructor dashboard (instructors).

The system has three runtime components:
  • VR Client         — Unreal Engine 5.5.4 mobile XR app
  • Signaling Server  — Node.js + Express + Socket.IO
  • Web Dashboard     — Vanilla JS/HTML/CSS instructor SPA

A trainee in a headset is paired to an instructor in a browser via a
4-digit code. The instructor sees the trainee's POV (720p/30fps over
Agora WebRTC), talks bidirectionally, and dispatches JSON commands that
drive in-simulation behavior.


# 1. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE & INFRASTRUCTURE
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1.1 VR Client (Unreal Engine 5.5.4)
- Engine version is **locked to UE 5.5.4** — do not generate code or
  Blueprint guidance that depends on engine APIs from other versions.
- Target hardware:
    • Meta Quest 3              (Snapdragon XR2 Gen 2)
    • Pico 4 Enterprise         (Snapdragon XR2 Gen 1)
- Build target: **Android, ASTC texture compression**.
- Refresh rate budget: **72 Hz minimum, 90 Hz preferred**.
- Rendering: Mobile forward renderer, Vulkan preferred, MSAA 4x where
  GPU headroom permits.
- All real-time logic that runs per-frame MUST be Blueprint-exposed C++
  or carefully optimized Blueprints. Avoid Tick-driven work where an
  event-driven approach is possible.

## 1.2 Signaling / Command Server
- Runtime: **Node.js (LTS)**, framework: **Express**, transport:
  **Socket.IO** (WebSockets) for bi-directional state sync.
- Payloads: **JSON only**. No binary frames over the command channel.
- Hosts pairing rooms keyed by the 4-digit code; relays commands from
  the instructor browser to the matching headset socket.
- Stateless across restarts is acceptable for v1, but reconnect logic
  on the client side (see §2.A.4) must tolerate brief server restarts.

## 1.3 Video / Audio Streaming Engine
- Provider: **Agora RTC SDK**.
- Video pipeline on the headset (Phase 7 — frame hijacking, verified Quest 3):
    UE stereo frame → `URenderHijackingSubsystem` /
    `FSceneColorCopyViewExtension` (right-eye copy, 1280×720) →
    `BP_InstructorViewLogic` composite (`M_InstructorView` +
    `DrawMaterialToRenderTarget`) → `RT_InstructorView` →
    `UAgoraVideoPump::SourceRT` → push as **custom video source**
    to Agora. Optional Quest MR overlay via `set_mr_mode` +
    AndroidMedia `vidcap://rear` (Pico MR no-ops cleanly).
- Legacy fallback (deprecated, kept disabled in `BP_VRPawn` for
  revert only): SceneCaptureComponent2D → `RT_InstructorStream`.
- Streaming spec is **HARD-LOCKED** at:
    • Resolution : **1280 × 720**
    • Framerate  : **30 fps**
    • Codec      : Agora default (H.264 baseline preferred for mobile)
  These numbers protect the XR2 thermal/perf envelope and prevent
  user motion sickness. Do not propose higher resolutions or framerates
  without an explicit instruction to override this rule.
- Audio: **bi-directional voice**. Instructor hears the VR session
  audio AND can speak to the trainee. The headset publishes its mic +
  game audio mix; the browser publishes the instructor's mic.

## 1.4 Network Topology
- **Video / Audio** : Peer-to-Peer or Agora CDN (WebRTC).
- **Commands / Pairing** : Centralized Socket.IO server.
- These two planes are **independent**. A failure in one plane MUST
  NOT take down the other (e.g., losing the video stream must not
  drop command control, and vice versa).


# 2. DETAILED UX WORKFLOWS
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 2.A  VR User Experience (Headset)
1. **Launch & Code Generation**
   On app launch, generate a unique randomized **4-digit pairing
   code** and display it on a floating **World-Space UMG widget** in
   the main menu.
2. **Waiting State**
   Headset registers the code with the Node.js server via WebSockets
   and remains in a "waiting for instructor" idle state.
3. **Session Active**
   When the instructor enters the matching code, the 3D code widget
   **fades out** and is replaced by a subtle "Instructor Connected"
   status indicator (small, non-intrusive, anchored to the HUD).
4. **Connection Resilience**
   On transient Wi-Fi loss, the headset MUST persistently retry
   reconnection using the **same 4-digit code**. The instructor's
   session resumes automatically — the instructor never re-enters
   the code. Use exponential backoff with a sane cap (e.g., 1s, 2s,
   4s, 8s, max 15s) and surface a discreet "Reconnecting…" UI hint.
5. **Command Reception**
   Headset subscribes to a JSON command channel and dispatches
   incoming payloads to native gameplay/simulation events
   (see §5 for the canonical schema).

## 2.B  Web Instructor Experience (Browser)
1. **Gatekeeping** — Landing page is a clean 4-digit code input. No
   accounts, no extra chrome.
2. **Connection** — A valid code joins the instructor into the
   matching Socket.IO room AND the matching Agora video/audio channel.
3. **The Control Center** — Two-column split layout:
   - **Left Panel (Stream View)**
       Low-latency 720p/30fps video feed of the trainee POV, plus
       mic mute, speaker mute, and volume controls.
   - **Right Panel (Control Deck)** — Interactive UI components that
       dispatch the canonical JSON commands defined in §5.2.


# 3. PROJECT DIRECTORY STRUCTURE
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Repository root layout:

    /VR_Project/        Unreal Engine 5.5.4 project
        Source/         C++ modules
        Content/        Blueprints, assets, UMG widgets
        Config/         DefaultEngine.ini, DefaultGame.ini, etc.
        *.uproject      Project descriptor
        # NEVER edit or commit: Binaries/, Saved/, Intermediate/,
        # DerivedDataCache/, Build/  (already in .gitignore)

    /Web_Dashboard/     Node.js backend + static instructor SPA
        server.js       Express + Socket.IO entry point
        package.json    Dependencies & npm scripts
        public/         Static front-end assets
            index.html  Landing + dashboard markup
            css/        CSS (vanilla, CSS variables)
            js/         Vanilla JS modules

Rules:
- Do not invent sibling top-level directories without explicit request.
- Do not rename or relocate engine-generated UE paths.
- All web back-end code lives in `/Web_Dashboard/`; all engine code
  lives in `/VR_Project/`. Cross-language utilities (e.g., a shared
  JSON command schema doc) belong in `/Web_Dashboard/docs/` or a
  clearly named `/shared/` folder — ask before creating new top-level
  folders.


# 4. CODE GENERATION RULES
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4.1 Universal
- Write modular, clean, well-documented code.
- Comments explain **intent / non-obvious constraints**, never narrate
  the obvious. Prefer self-describing names over comments.
- Every public function/class gets a docstring or header comment with
  purpose, parameters, and side effects.
- No silent failure paths — log + surface every error meaningfully.
- Never hard-code secrets, API keys, App IDs, or tokens. Load from
  environment variables (`.env`, never committed) on the server, and
  from a config asset (not source-controlled) on the UE side.

## 4.2 Unreal Engine (C++ / Blueprints)
- Prefer **Blueprint-exposed C++** for any logic that runs hot,
  touches networking, or implements core gameplay services.
- Use Blueprints for UI wiring, designer-tunable parameters, and
  level-specific scripting.
- Naming:
    • C++ classes:       `UMyManager`, `AMyActor`, `FMyStruct`
    • Blueprint assets:  `BP_PairingManager`, `WBP_CodeWidget`,
                          `M_HUDStatus`, `T_LogoAtlas`
- UMG widgets that exist in 3D space MUST be World-Space and use
  signed-distance-field fonts for legibility at HMD resolution.
- Networking & async work:
    • Use `FHttpModule` only for non-realtime REST calls.
    • Use a dedicated Socket.IO C++ plugin (e.g., SocketIOClient) for
      the command channel. Wrap it in a single `USignalingSubsystem`
      (UGameInstanceSubsystem) so the rest of the codebase only
      depends on a clean Blueprint-callable API.
    • Use a dedicated Agora UE plugin for video/audio.
- Performance:
    • Instructor stream: frame hijacking at 1280×720 (no second
      scene render). `BP_InstructorViewLogic` composites to
      `RT_InstructorView` on a 30 Hz tick/timer — NOT every engine
      tick at full rate.
    • `RT_InstructorView` format MUST be `RTF_RGBA8_SRGB` (same
      linear/sRGB readback rule as the legacy SceneCapture path).
    • If using the legacy SceneCapture fallback: 1280×720 only,
      fixed 30 Hz timer, `bCaptureEveryFrame=false`, reuse one RT.
    • Avoid dynamic material instance creation on hot paths.
    • No `Tick` on actors that don't need it — set
      `PrimaryActorTick.bCanEverTick = false` by default.

## 4.3 Web Back-End (Node.js / Express / Socket.IO)
- ES2022+, `"type": "module"` in `package.json`, use `import`/`export`.
- Keep `server.js` thin; factor handlers into `/Web_Dashboard/src/`:
    • `pairing.js`   — room creation, code registry, lookup
    • `commands.js`  — command relay + schema validation
    • `agora.js`     — token minting (server-side, never client-side)
- Validate every incoming Socket.IO payload against the §5 schema
  before relaying. Reject unknown commands with a typed error event.
- Use environment variables via `process.env` (load with `dotenv`
  in development only).

### 4.3.1 Agora Account Topology — v1 Decision
- **Topology: Option A — single shared Agora project.** ONE Agora
  App ID and App Certificate are used for all tenants/customers.
- Credentials live ONLY on the server, in env vars:
      AGORA_APP_ID            (safe to expose in tokens, never hard-coded)
      AGORA_APP_CERTIFICATE   (server-side secret, NEVER sent to clients)
- Tenant isolation is achieved by **channel naming convention**, not
  by separate Agora projects. Canonical channel name format:
      `t-<tenantId>-<pairingCode>`
  This keeps a future migration to one-project-per-tenant trivial.
- The token-minting function MUST take `tenantId` as a parameter
  even though, in v1, every tenant resolves to the same App ID /
  Certificate. Do not read the credentials inline at the call site;
  go through a `getAgoraCredentials(tenantId)` lookup so swapping
  to per-tenant credentials later is a one-file change.
- Tokens are **short-lived (30–60 min)** and refreshed by the client
  SDK mid-session. Do not mint long-lived tokens.
- Every token issuance writes a usage row
  (`tenantId, seatId, channel, role, issuedAt, expiresAt`) for
  later billing/subscription reconciliation — even if v1 has no
  active subscription gating yet.

## 4.4 Web Front-End (Vanilla JS / HTML5 / CSS)
- **Vanilla JS only** — no React/Vue/Svelte/jQuery unless explicitly
  requested. Use native ES modules (`<script type="module">`).
- HTML5 semantic elements (`<main>`, `<section>`, `<aside>`, etc.).
- CSS uses **CSS Custom Properties (variables)** for theming. Define
  the design tokens in a single `:root { … }` block in
  `public/css/tokens.css`.
- Aim for a modern, clean aesthetic: generous spacing, sans-serif
  system font stack, soft shadows, rounded corners, high contrast.
- No build step required for v1 — code must run as plain static
  assets served by Express.

## 4.5 Terminal Commands
- Before providing any terminal command in chat output, **explicitly
  state the target directory** the command must be run from. Example:

      # From /Web_Dashboard/
      npm install socket.io express


# 5. COMMUNICATION CONTRACTS
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 5.1 Pairing (Socket.IO events)
- `headset:register`     payload: `{ "code": "1234", "tenantId"?: string,
                                      "scenario"?: string, "traineeName"?: string,
                                      "source"?: "headset"|"faker",
                                      "appId"?: string, "appVersion"?: string }`
                         emitted by: VR client on launch / reconnect
                         Note: appId / appVersion (added 2026-06-15) enable
                         the per-app interactive control plane (§5.3).
- `instructor:join`      payload: `{ "code": "1234" }`
                         emitted by: web dashboard on submit (legacy 1:1 mode)
- `instructor:subscribe-tenant`
                         payload: `{}` (tenantId read from session cookie)
                         emitted by: grid-view instructors on connect
- `headset:end`          payload: `{ "code": "1234" }`
                         emitted by: VR client on Deinitialize (graceful shutdown)
- `session:status`       payload: `{ "state": "waiting" | "connected" | "reconnecting" | "ended" }`
                         emitted by: server → both peers
- `session:end`          payload: `{ "reason": "string" }`
- `sessions:changed`     payload: `{ "tenantId": string, "sessions": [...] }`
                         emitted by: server → instructor sockets in tenant room

## 5.2 Canonical Command Payloads (Instructor → Headset)
All commands are JSON objects with at minimum a `command` field. The
following four MUST be supported exactly as specified:

  • Pause / Resume Simulation
        { "command": "pause_simulation", "value": true | false }

  • Environment Changer
        { "command": "change_environment", "map_name": "string" }

  • Training Intervention (trigger event)
        { "command": "trigger_event", "event_type": "string" }

  • User Reset
        { "command": "reset_user_position" }

The following is app-agnostic in *protocol* but opt-in in *implementation*
(pure-VR apps without passthrough capability are expected to no-op cleanly
per the unknown-command rule below):

  • Set Mixed-Reality Mode (added 2026-06-15, Phase 7 instructor-view rebuild)
        { "command": "set_mr_mode", "enabled": true | false }

Rules:
- Field names are `snake_case` in JSON (consistent with the spec).
- Unknown commands MUST be ignored by the headset and logged by the
  server. Never crash on a malformed payload.
- Extensions are allowed but must be additive and documented in
  `/Web_Dashboard/docs/commands.md`.

App-specific commands (added 2026-06-15) live in the same command channel
but are scoped to a specific `appId` declared on `headset:register`. The
server validates them against `APP_COMMAND_VALIDATORS[<appId>]` in
`Web_Dashboard/src/commands.js`, falling back to the four cross-app
commands above. Per-appId schema + reference VRFT module documented in
`/Web_Dashboard/docs/commands.md` (App-specific commands section).

## 5.3 State updates (Headset → Instructor)

Added 2026-06-15. The inverse direction of §5.2 — a headset publishes its
app-specific state machine transitions so the dashboard can render a
per-app instructor UI (level picker, scenario status, in-level controls).
Event: `headset:state-update` (headset → server), fan-out as
`session:state-changed` (server → instructors). Wire format + per-appId
state-machine conventions: `/Web_Dashboard/docs/state-updates.md`.

Same rules as §5.2 apply: snake_case JSON, additive extensions, never
crash on malformed input. Server caches the latest state per room +
size-caps data payloads at 8 KB. Per-app dashboard modules live at
`/Web_Dashboard/public/js/apps/<appId>.js`; convention in
`/Web_Dashboard/public/js/apps/README.md`.


# 6. PERFORMANCE & QUALITY BARS
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
- VR frame time budget: **≤ 13.8 ms** (72 Hz) — hard ceiling.
- Video capture cost: target ≤ 2.0 ms GPU per captured frame at 720p.
- Command end-to-end latency target: **≤ 150 ms** instructor click →
  headset event dispatch on a healthy LAN.
- Video glass-to-glass latency target: **≤ 400 ms** via Agora.
- Reconnect time after Wi-Fi blip target: **≤ 5 s** to "connected".
- Dashboard first paint: **≤ 1 s** on a modern desktop browser.


# 7. ANTI-PATTERNS — DO NOT DO
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
- ❌ Do not raise stream resolution or framerate above 720p/30fps.
- ❌ Do not re-enable SceneCapture for the instructor stream when
  the hijack path is active — it doubles GPU cost for no benefit.
- ❌ Do not drive SceneCapture from Tick or capture every frame
  (legacy path only).
- ❌ Do not put Agora App IDs, tokens, or any secret in client code.
- ❌ Do not introduce a front-end framework (React/Vue/etc.) without
     explicit instruction.
- ❌ Do not require the instructor to re-enter the code after a
     headset Wi-Fi blip — reconnect is the headset's responsibility.
- ❌ Do not bypass the §5.2 JSON schema with ad-hoc message shapes.
- ❌ Do not edit or commit UE engine-generated folders
     (Binaries/, Saved/, Intermediate/, DerivedDataCache/, Build/).
- ❌ Do not commit large binary assets without confirming they match
     a Git LFS pattern in `.gitattributes`.
- ❌ Do not assume an internet-facing deployment without asking —
     v1 may run on a LAN.


# 8. BUILD & DEPLOYMENT PIPELINE (UE VR CLIENT)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This is the verified-working build and deployment loop for the standalone
# mobile VR client. When the user asks to "build", "package", "deploy", or
# "make a new build", execute this pipeline exactly. Do not improvise flags
# or paths without explicit instruction.

## 8.1 Headset Deployment Pre-requisites (verify before invoking the pipeline)
1. Meta Quest 3 or Pico 4 Enterprise is connected to the PC via a USB-C
   **data** cable (charge-only cables will not enumerate).
2. Developer Mode is toggled ON in the device's mobile companion app
   (Meta Quest app / PICO Business app).
3. USB Debugging is authorized on the headset screen — choose
   "Always allow from this computer".
4. `adb devices` lists the headset serial with status **`device`**
   (not `unauthorized`, not `offline`, not missing).
5. PowerShell execution policy allows running unsigned local scripts —
   the canonical cook entry point (`Tools/Cook-VRApp.ps1`) is unsigned.
   One-time setup: `Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser RemoteSigned`.
   Per-invocation alternative: `powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File
   .\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 ...`. (Bypassing globally with `-Scope
   LocalMachine Unrestricted` is **not** recommended — keeps the
   "remote scripts must be signed" half of the protection.)

If any of the five conditions fails, **stop and report** — do not attempt
the build, because `-deploy -run` will fail late and waste a full cook.

## 8.2 The Canonical Build Pipeline

**Use the per-device cook wrapper as the entry point:**

    .\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 -Device quest        # cook + deploy to Quest 3
    .\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 -Device pico         # cook + deploy to Pico 4 Enterprise
    .\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1                      # auto-detect from `adb devices`

The wrapper exists because Quest and Pico require different
`[HMDPluginPriority]` blocks in `DefaultEngine.ini` (Quest needs
`OpenXR=10, PICOXRHMD=0`; Pico needs `OpenXR=0, PICOXRHMD=10` — see
Devlog 2026-06-08 for the full diagnosis of why neither value works
universally on PICO OS 5+). The wrapper temporarily mutates the INI
for the duration of one cook, runs UAT verbatim per the command
below, restores the INI via a guaranteed `try/finally` block, and
renames the produced APK to `VR_Project-Quest-arm64.apk` /
`VR_Project-Pico-arm64.apk` so both vendors' APKs co-exist on disk.

**Underlying UAT command** (what the wrapper invokes — preserved verbatim
here as the authoritative reference). Run from `/VR_Project/` in a
**Windows Command Prompt** (not PowerShell — `%CD%` expansion differs).
If invoked from PowerShell, wrap with `cmd /c "<command>"`.

    "C:\Program Files\Epic Games\UE_5.5\Engine\Build\BatchFiles\RunUAT.bat" ^
      BuildCookRun ^
      -project="%CD%\VR_Project.uproject" ^
      -targetplatform=Android ^
      -cookflavor=ASTC ^
      -clientconfig=Development ^
      -build -cook -stage -package -archive ^
      -archivedirectory="%CD%\Build" ^
      -deploy -run

Only invoke this command directly when (a) debugging the wrapper
itself, (b) the dev's only test device is connected and they've
already confirmed the INI's baseline `[HMDPluginPriority]` matches
that device (baseline is Quest), or (c) reproducing a UAT-side issue
in isolation. Otherwise use the wrapper — it eliminates a class of
"wrong APK installed" / "INI left flipped after a crash" mistakes.

## 8.3 Flag Reference
- `-build`     : Generates editor targets and compiles native runtime modules.
- `-cook`      : Bakes project assets into mobile-optimized formats (ASTC).
- `-stage`     : Lays out cooked content into a deployable directory tree.
- `-package`   : Bundles staged content + binaries into the Android APK.
- `-archive`   : Copies the final artifacts to `-archivedirectory`.
- `-deploy`    : Installs the APK on the connected headset over ADB.
- `-run`       : Launches the app on the headset after install.

## 8.4 Variants (only use when explicitly requested)
- **Package only, no device push** — `.\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 -Device <d> -NoDeploy`.
  Drops `-deploy -run` from the UAT command. Useful when no headset is
  connected or when producing a build for sideload elsewhere.
- **Shipping config** — `.\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 -Device <d> -Configuration Shipping`.
  Expect longer compile and smaller APK with no debug symbols. Do not
  use for daily iteration.
- **Clean build** — prepend a manual delete of
  `VR_Project\Binaries\`, `VR_Project\Intermediate\`,
  `VR_Project\Saved\StagedBuilds\`, and `VR_Project\Build\` only when
  the user explicitly asks for a clean rebuild. Never delete
  `DerivedDataCache/` automatically (very expensive to repopulate).
- **Validate the wrapper without burning a cook** —
  `.\Tools\Cook-VRApp.ps1 -Device pico -DryRun`. Mutates + restores the
  INI without invoking UAT. Run after editing the wrapper or after a
  failed cook that left you wondering whether the restore semantics
  held (the script's `git status` pre-flight check is also a safety
  net there).

## 8.5 Known Failure Signatures → Resolutions
Reference the Devlog `System Remediation History` section for full
context. Short triage table:

| Failure signature                                          | Likely cause                                | Resolution location |
|------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|---------------------|
| `java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: javax/xml/bind/...XmlSchema` | `cmdline-tools\latest\` symlink missing  | Devlog §3           |
| `ExitCode=51 (Error_FailureGettingPackageInfo)`            | Missing `PackageName` or `-package` flag    | Devlog §4           |
| `JAVA_HOME` points to `\jre\`                              | Legacy Android Studio variable layout       | Devlog §2           |
| `NDK_ROOT` / `NDKROOT` pointing to old NDK                 | Stale env vars from legacy install          | Devlog §2           |
| `adb devices` shows headset as `unauthorized`              | USB debug dialog not accepted on headset    | §8.1                |

## 8.6 Output Artifacts
On success, the deployable APK lives at:

    /VR_Project/Binaries/Android/VR_Project-Quest-arm64.apk      (Quest cook)
    /VR_Project/Binaries/Android/VR_Project-Pico-arm64.apk       (Pico cook)

(The wrapper renames UE's default `VR_Project-arm64.apk` to one of the
above after a successful UAT run, so both vendors' APKs co-exist on
disk without overwriting each other.)

Staging + archive companion files land in:

    /VR_Project/Build/Android_ASTC/

When `-NoDeploy` is omitted (the default), the headset already has the
APK installed and the template map running. Confirm by tailing the last
lines of the UAT log for `BUILD SUCCESSFUL` and `Deploy Time: ...` markers.


